S2_MGF Figure 1: Map

Stephen Formel

10/15/2021

Figure 1: Map of Oil Distribution

Description: Demonstrate distribution of PAHs at sites and time points.

Note that winter = time point 1 and summer = time point 2. This is leftover from earilier analyses. I was asked to change these terms in the manuscript revisions, and I didnt have time to completely revise the scripts.

Notes:

  • My foundation came from this tutorial: http://zevross.com/blog/2014/07/16/mapping-in-r-using-the-ggplot2-package/
  • BJ is shorthand for Bay Jimmy site, F is shorthand for Fourchon site.
  • Publicly available shape files for marsh sites didnt capture the scale we needed for this map. Shape files for sites were made by hand tracing sites in Google maps, exporting it as a KML file and importing that into ArcGIS to make a shape file.

Set up environment

Load Libraries

library(rgdal)
library(ggsn)
library(cowplot)
library(tidyverse)
library(plyr)

Make colorblind-safe color palette

cPAL <- c("#E69F00", "#0072B2")
  1. Load and clean data
source("./S2_MGF_load_packages_and_clean_data.R")

#This loads in way more objects than are needed for this script, but the above was a very handy script during data exploration and it never bogged my computer down to have all these objects loaded in at the beginning.
  1. Extract oil data and omit any samples without oil data (NA)
voi <- fung.2season_with_outliers

df.env <- data.frame(sample_data(voi))

#recode variables
df.env$site <- plyr:::revalue(x = df.env$site, replace = c("BJ" = "Bay Jimmy", "F" = "Fourchon"))
df.env$season <- plyr:::revalue(x = df.env$season, replace = c("WINTER" = "Time Point 1", "SUMMER" = "Time Point 2"))

#clean and select variables of interest
df.PAHs <- df.env %>%
  select(SampleID,
         site,
         season,
         Total.C1.C3.chrysenes,
         Total.C1.C4.naphthalenes,
         Total.C1.C3.dibenzothiophenes,
         Total.C1.C4.phenanthrenes,
         Total.relevant.PAHs,
         Longitude,
         Latitude) %>%
  na.omit() %>% 
  gather(key = "Class", 
         value = "Abundance", 
         Total.C1.C3.chrysenes:Total.C1.C4.phenanthrenes)

df.PAHs.maps <- df.env %>%
  select(SampleID,
         site,
         season,
         Total.relevant.PAHs,
         Longitude,
         Latitude) %>%
  na.omit()
  1. Make Bay Jimmy site map.
#read in BJ shapefile
BJ.shp <- readOGR("../data/GIS/BJ_site.shp")
## OGR data source with driver: ESRI Shapefile 
## Source: "/Volumes/GoogleDrive/My Drive/VB_lab/VBL_data/Collections/S2_MG collection/S2_MG/data/GIS/BJ_site.shp", layer: "BJ_site"
## with 1 features
## It has 12 fields
## Integer64 fields read as strings:  OID_ SymbolID
## Warning in readOGR("../data/GIS/BJ_site.shp"): Z-dimension discarded
#check projection, should be WGS84
proj4string(BJ.shp)
## Warning in proj4string(BJ.shp): CRS object has comment, which is lost in output
## [1] "+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84 +no_defs"
# Next the shapefile has to be converted to a dataframe for use in ggplot2
BJ.shp_df <- fortify(BJ.shp)
## Regions defined for each Polygons
#make our data object unique so we don't have to back transform it after this
df.env.na.maps <- df.PAHs.maps

#make it spatial points
coordinates(df.env.na.maps) <- ~ Longitude + Latitude

#we know that the coordinate system is WGS84 (google maps) so we can manually tell R what the coordinate system is
proj4string(df.env.na.maps)<-CRS("+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84 +no_defs +ellps=WGS84 +towgs84=0,0,0")

#now we can use the spTransform function to project. We will project the mapdata and for coordinate reference system (CRS) we will assign the projection from counties

df.env.na.maps<-spTransform(df.env.na.maps, CRS(proj4string(BJ.shp)))
## Warning in proj4string(BJ.shp): CRS object has comment, which is lost in output
# double check that they match
identical(proj4string(df.env.na.maps),proj4string(BJ.shp))
## Warning in proj4string(df.env.na.maps): CRS object has comment, which is lost in output
## Warning in proj4string(BJ.shp): CRS object has comment, which is lost in output
## [1] TRUE
# ggplot can't deal with a SpatialPointsDataFrame so we can convert back to a data.frame
df.env.na.maps_df <- data.frame(df.env.na.maps)

#subset for BJ
df.env.na.maps_df.BJ <- df.env.na.maps_df[df.env.na.maps_df$site=="Bay Jimmy",]

#Make plot

map <- ggplot() +
  geom_polygon(data = BJ.shp_df, 
               aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group),
               color = "black", 
               fill = "lightgray", 
               size = .2,
               alpha = 0.3)

map.styled <- map +
  geom_point(data=df.env.na.maps_df.BJ, 
             aes(x=Longitude, 
                 y=Latitude, 
                 size= sqrt(Total.relevant.PAHs), 
                 fill = season), 
             shape = 21, 
             color = "black", 
             position=position_jitter(width = 0.00004, height = 0.00004)) +
  scale_size(range = c(rel(0), rel(10))) +
  theme_void() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = cPAL) +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

#Add north arrow and scale bar
BJ.map.no.inset <- map.styled +
  north(BJ.shp_df, 
        location = "bottomleft", 
        anchor = c(x = -89.8909, y = 29.443)) +
  scalebar(BJ.shp_df, 
           dist = 0.1, 
           dist_unit = "km", 
           transform = TRUE, 
           model = 'WGS84', 
           location = "bottomleft", 
           st.size = 2.5, 
           border.size = 0.1)

#check projection on our data

## Warning in proj4string(LA.shp.tran): CRS object has comment, which is lost in output

identical(proj4string(LA.shp.tran),proj4string(BJ.shp))

## Warning in proj4string(LA.shp.tran): CRS object has comment, which is lost in output

  1. Put together Bay Jimmy site and Inset
#Bay Jimmy site map
BJ.site <- BJ.map.no.inset +
  annotation_custom(grob = LA.inset, xmin = -89.8852, xmax = -89.8878, ymin = 29.4440, ymax = 29.44575)

  1. Make strip plot of PAH classes for Bay Jimmy site
#make BJ plot
df.PAHs.plot.BJ <- ggplot(data = df.PAHs[df.PAHs$site=="Bay Jimmy",], 
                          aes(x = Class, 
                              y = Abundance, 
                              color = season, 
                              fill = season, 
                              shape = site)) + 
  geom_jitter(size = 4,
              width = 0.2, 
              stroke = 1, 
              alpha = 3/5) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c(rep("black", 4)), 
                     name = "Season") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = cPAL, 
                    name = "Season") +
  scale_shape_manual(values = c(21,24), 
                     name = "Site") +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(panel.border = element_rect(color="black", fill=NA), 
        axis.title.x = element_blank(), 
        text=element_text(size=14), 
        legend.position = "none", 
        axis.text.x = element_blank(),
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
  labs(y = paste0("PAHs (", "\U03BC", "g/g)")) +
  scale_y_log10(labels = function(x) format(x, scientific = FALSE)) +
  scale_x_discrete(labels = c("Total.C1.C3.chrysenes" = "C1-C3 chrysenes", 
                              "Total.C1.C4.naphthalenes" =  "C1-C4 naphthalenes", 
                              "Total.C1.C4.phenanthrenes" = "C1-C4 phenanthrenes", 
                              "Total.C1.C3.dibenzothiophenes" = "C1-C3 dibenzothiophenes") ) +
  ggtitle(" Bay Jimmy")
  1. Get legend for final figure
legend <- get_legend(ggplot(data = df.PAHs[df.PAHs$site=="Bay Jimmy",], 
                            aes(x = Class, 
                                y = Abundance, 
                                color = season, 
                                fill = season)) + 
                       geom_jitter(size = 4,
                                   width = 0.2, 
                                   stroke = 1, 
                                   alpha = 3/5, 
                                   shape = 21) +
                       scale_shape_manual(values= c(21, 21), 
                                          name = "Time Point") +
                       scale_color_manual(values = c(rep("black", 4)), 
                                          name = "Time Point") +
                       scale_fill_manual(values = cPAL, 
                                         name = "Time Point") +
                       theme(legend.position="bottom", 
                             legend.direction="horizontal", 
                             legend.justification="center"))
  1. Make Fourchon site strip plot
df.PAHs.plot.F <- ggplot(data = df.PAHs[df.PAHs$site=="Fourchon",], 
                          aes(x = Class,

                              "Total.C1.C4.phenanthrenes" = "C1-C4 phenanthrenes", 
                              "Total.C1.C3.dibenzothiophenes" = "C1-C3 dibenzothiophenes") ) +
  ggtitle("Fourchon")
  1. Build final figure
left <- plot_grid(df.PAHs.plot.BJ, 
                  df.PAHs.plot.F, 
                  legend, 
                  nrow = 3, 
                  rel_heights = c(0.6, 1, 0.1), 
                  labels = c("a", "b"), 
                  align = "V")

right <- plot_grid(BJ.site, 
                   F.map.no.inset, 
                   nrow = 2, 
                   labels = c("c", "d"))

#final plot

plot_grid(left, 
          right, 
          ncol = 2, 
          rel_widths = c(1,0.75))
